            <div class="contain2">
                <div class="movie-text">
                    <h4>My name is Khan</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>My Name Is Khan (2010) tells the story of Rizwan Khan, a Muslim man with Asperger’s syndrome, who moves to the U.S. and marries Mandira, a Hindu woman with a young son. After the 9/11 attacks, the family faces increasing discrimination, leading to the tragic death of their son, Sameer, in a hate-fueled assault. Mandira blames Rizwan’s religion for their loss and challenges him to prove to the world—and to the President—that he is not a terrorist.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Rizwan sets out on a cross-country journey, determined to meet the President and convey his message: “My name is Khan, and I am not a terrorist.” Along the way, he encounters people of all backgrounds, spreading kindness and challenging prejudice. Rizwan’s journey becomes a national story, symbolizing resilience and the power of love. In the end, he reunites with Mandira, highlighting the film’s themes of acceptance, humanity, and the rejection of hate.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="movie-text">
                    <h4>Veer Zara</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Veer-Zaara (2004) is a Bollywood romantic drama directed by Yash Chopra, starring Shah Rukh Khan as Veer, an Indian Air Force pilot, and Preity Zinta as Zaara, a Pakistani woman from a prominent family. The film explores the transcendent love between Veer and Zaara, who meet when Veer saves her during a pilgrimage to India. Despite their love, societal and familial pressures force them apart, with Veer being wrongfully imprisoned in Pakistan for years to protect Zaara’s honor.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Years later, a young Pakistani lawyer, Saamiya (played by Rani Mukerji), discovers Veer’s case and seeks justice, uncovering the powerful love story between the star-crossed lovers. The film’s themes of love, sacrifice, and unity across borders are beautifully portrayed, supported by a timeless soundtrack by the late Madan Mohan. Veer-Zaara delivers a heartfelt message on humanity and the power of love beyond cultural and political barriers, making it a memorable and emotional cinematic experience.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="movie-text">
                    <h4>Jab tak hai Jaan</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Jab Tak Hai Jaan (2012), directed by Yash Chopra, is a Bollywood romance starring Shah Rukh Khan, Katrina Kaif, and Anushka Sharma. The story follows Samar Anand (Khan), a bomb disposal expert in the Indian Army, who previously lived in London, where he fell deeply in love with Meera (Kaif). Their passionate romance faces an unexpected turn when Meera, bound by a promise to God, leaves Samar to keep him safe after he survives a life-threatening accident.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Heartbroken, Samar returns to India and becomes fearless in the face of death, taking on the dangerous job of defusing bombs. Years later, Akira (Sharma), a young documentary filmmaker, meets him and becomes fascinated by his story, sparking her own feelings for him. When Samar suffers memory loss and is taken back to London, he and Meera are forced to confront their past. The film is an emotional journey exploring love, destiny, sacrifice, and faith, beautifully complemented by A.R. Rahman’s soulful music. Jab Tak Hai Jaan is a tribute to undying love, marked by Yash Chopra’s signature storytelling style, making it a heartfelt cinematic experience.
                        </p></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="movie-text">
                    <h4>Om shanthi Om</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Om Shanti Om (2007), directed by Farah Khan, is a Bollywood film that blends romance, comedy, and reincarnation drama, starring Shah Rukh Khan and Deepika Padukone in her debut role. The story follows Om Prakash Makhija (Khan), a junior film artist in the 1970s, who falls in love with superstar Shanti Priya (Padukone). Tragically, Om witnesses Shanti’s murder by her lover, producer Mukesh Mehra (Arjun Rampal), and dies attempting to save her.</p></li>
                        <li><p>In his next life, Om is reborn as a successful Bollywood star, Om Kapoor, with faint memories of his past. As these memories resurface, he embarks on a mission to avenge Shanti’s death and bring her killer to justice. The film is filled with nostalgic references to Bollywood’s golden era, a captivating soundtrack, and extravagant dance numbers. Om Shanti Om is a highly entertaining mix of romance, suspense, and comedy, celebrating the magic and drama of Bollywood itself. Its themes of love, revenge, and destiny make it a memorable, colorful, and uniquely satisfying cinematic experience.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
